<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="589" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,258,931]" pageId="2" pageNumber="589">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,726,751]" pageId="2" pageNumber="589">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is very similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Li &amp; Li, 2011" authorityName="Li &amp; Li" authorityYear="2011" box="[719,1127,726,751]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Angustella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="589" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jinghongensis">
<emphasis box="[719,914,726,750]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="589">A. jinghongensis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Li" box="[937,1119,726,751]" pageId="2" pageNumber="589" refString="Li, Y. J. &amp; Li, Z. Z. (2011) Notes on the leafhopper genus Angustella Li (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae: Evacanthinae), with descriptions of four new species from China. Zootaxa, 2740, 44 - 52." type="journal article" year="2011">
Li &amp; Li, 
<number box="[1062,1119,727,751]" pageId="2" pageNumber="589" value="2011.0">2011</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
externally, but it can be distinguished from the latter by: 
<number box="[522,534,763,787]" pageId="2" pageNumber="589" value="1.0">1</number>
) lorum (
<figureCitation box="[636,704,762,787]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1923,1946]" captionTargetBox="[186,1415,203,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[166,1420,190,1902]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 10. Angustuma basinigra sp. nov.: 1. male habitus, dorsal view; 2. male habitus, lateral view; 3. male head and thorax, dorsal view; 4. male face; 5. male pygofer, lateral view; 6. male pygofer side, lateral view; 7. aedeagal, lateral view; 8. aedeagal, ventral view; 9. connective and style, ventral view; 10. subgenital plate, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227639/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="589">
Fig. 
<number box="[689,704,763,787]" pageId="2" pageNumber="589" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
) black at base, pale in latter; 
<number box="[1039,1054,763,787]" pageId="2" pageNumber="589" value="2.0">2</number>
) each forewing (
<figureCitation box="[1247,1348,762,787]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1923,1946]" captionTargetBox="[186,1415,203,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[166,1420,190,1902]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 10. Angustuma basinigra sp. nov.: 1. male habitus, dorsal view; 2. male habitus, lateral view; 3. male head and thorax, dorsal view; 4. male face; 5. male pygofer, lateral view; 6. male pygofer side, lateral view; 7. aedeagal, lateral view; 8. aedeagal, ventral view; 9. connective and style, ventral view; 10. subgenital plate, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227639/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="589">Figs 1, 2</figureCitation>
) with 
<number box="[1422,1436,763,787]" pageId="2" pageNumber="589" value="2.0">2</number>
thick stripes, latter with 
<number box="[427,441,799,823]" pageId="2" pageNumber="589" value="4.0">4</number>
thin stripes; 
<number box="[589,603,799,823]" pageId="2" pageNumber="589" value="3.0">3</number>
) aedeagal (
<figureCitation box="[735,803,798,823]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1923,1946]" captionTargetBox="[186,1415,203,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[166,1420,190,1902]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 10. Angustuma basinigra sp. nov.: 1. male habitus, dorsal view; 2. male habitus, lateral view; 3. male head and thorax, dorsal view; 4. male face; 5. male pygofer, lateral view; 6. male pygofer side, lateral view; 7. aedeagal, lateral view; 8. aedeagal, ventral view; 9. connective and style, ventral view; 10. subgenital plate, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227639/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="589">
Fig. 
<number box="[788,803,799,823]" pageId="2" pageNumber="589" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
) ventral apophysis in lateral view smaller than in latter, shape also different.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="589" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,258,931]" pageId="2" pageNumber="589">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,870,895]" pageId="2" pageNumber="589">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet, a combination of “basis” meaning basal, and “nigra” meaning black, refers to the lorum being black at base in these insects.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
